deck_excerpt: The 3rd Coming of Fiendsmith Prediction Princess (not)
deck_description:
Fiendsmith has received a second Level 9 monster in Fiendsmith’s Rex Tremendae which is a Level 9 LIGHT Fiend Fusion Monster which requires a Fiendsmith Fusion Monster and a Fusion or Link Monster as material. It is unaffected by non-Fiendsmith card effects while equipped with a Fiendsmith Equip Spell, if it is Fusion Summoned, you can discard a card to send a LIGHT Fiend monster from your Deck or Extra Deck to the GY, and if it is sent to the GY, you can target and add a Fiendsmith card from your GY or banishment to your hand. You are never summoning this card in the TCG. Not only is it harder to Fusion Summon than Fiendsmith’s Desirae due to the banning of Fiendsmith’s Lacrima, it functionally doesn’t do anything unless you are playing a dedicated pure Fiendsmith Deck or some Deck that warrants you needing to dump a LIGHT Fiend from Deck or Extra Deck so badly that you are actually Fusion Summoning this card. The best way you are Fusion Summoning this is if you are using the Desirae and the Fiendsmith’s Sequence you have already made as Fusion Material with the effect of Fiendsmith’s Tract or you can somehow get said Desirae from Extra Deck to GY without Summoning it first and using Sequence to shuffle it an another Fusion or Link Monster in GY into the Extra Deck to Fusion Summon Tremendae. Just make Desirae, don’t make this card. But since I want to test out every Level 9 in the game with Prediction Princess, here we are. It’s just a way worse version of a Post ROTA Fiendsmith Prediction Princess list. Don’t play this. If you want a Post Rota Fiendsmith Prediction Princess list, just take my Post INFO Fiendsmith Prediction Princess list and replace 1 Fiendsmith Engraver with Lacrima the Crimson Tears and either cut D/D/D Wave High King Caesar or S:P Little Knight for Fiendsmith’s Agnumday, and maybe cut Pot of Prosperity or something for a third Lonefire Blossom if you want. I’m gonna give 2 combos. The first is if you draw World Legacy Monstrosity and the second is if you don’t have Monstrosity. 

For the combo with Monstrosity, you just need Fiendsmith’s Tract and World Legacy Monstrosity. Activate Tract to add Fabled Lurrie and discard Lurrie. Lurrie triggers to Summon itself back. Link Lurrie into Fiendsmith’s Requiem. Activate Requiem Tributing itself to Summon Lacrima the Crimson Tears from Deck. Lacrima activates to send Fiendsmith Engraver from Deck to GY. Activate Requiem in GY to equip itself to Lacrima. Send both Lacrima and the equipped Requiem to GY to Special Summon Necroquip Princess from Extra Deck. Activate Engraver in GY, shuffling another LIGHT Fiend from GY into Deck to Special Summon it, let’s say you shuffled back Requiem. Link Necroquip and Engraver into Fiendsmith’s Sequence. Activate Sequence shuffling Engraver, Lacrima, and Lurrie into Deck to Fusion Summon Fiendsmith’s Desirae. Banish Tract from GY to Fuse Sequence and Desirae into Fiendsmith’s Rex Tremendae. Activate Monstrosity targeting it to Special Summon Deus-X Krawler and Prediction Princess Bibliomuse from Deck. Xyz Tremendae and Deus-X into Mereologic Aggregator, sending Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY and the rest is the same old Prediction Princess combo. 

For the combo without Monstrosity, you need Fiendsmith’s Tract, Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio, and a monster to send from hand to GY. Normal Scorpio discarding a monster to Special Summon Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra from Deck. Cobra activates to search for Instant Fusion. Activate Instant Fusion for Master of Ham who Special Summons Prediction Princess Bibliomuse from Deck. Banish Scorpio, Cobra, and Master of Ham for Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment. Activate Tract to search for Lurrie, discarding it, and it Summons itself back. Link it into Requiem who then Tributes itself to Special Summon Lacrima from Deck. Lacrima activates sending Engraver from Deck to GY. Activate Requiem in GY to equip itself to Lacrima. Send both of them to GY to Special Summon Necroquip Princess. Shuffle Requiem from GY into Deck to Special Summon the Engraver from GY. Link both Engraver and Necroquip into Fiendsmith’s Sequence. Sequence activates to shuffle Engraver, Lurrie, and Lacrima into Deck to Fusion Summon Fiendsmith’s Desirae. Xyz Desirae and Trishula into Mereologic Aggregator who sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY. Herald triggers to add Prediction Princess Tarotrei from Deck to hand. Aggregator activates targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1 material, and attaching the Herald from GY to itself. Link Aggregator and Sequence into Fiendsmith’s Agnumday. Herald triggers again to search for Underworld Ritual of Prediction. Activate Underworld Ritual Tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotrei. Bibliomuse triggers in Gy to Special Summon herself back face-down. Tarotrei flips Bibliomuse face-up and her Flip Effect triggers to add a Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual to hand. Underworld Ritual again tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down. End Phase, Tarotreith Special Summons Deus-X from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon a Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and use Tarotrei to flip Tarotreith face-up. You could activate Tarotreith’s Flip Effect to get Pot of the Forbidden from Deck face-down. Or, you can not activate her effect to use the effect of Agnumday who Special Summons the Desirae from your GY and equips itself to it as an Equip Card that gives it 1800 ATK, piercing, and the ability to negate 3 face-up cards on the field. Imagine this in a Deck where we aren’t focusing on making Rex Tremendae and we can play a lot more good cards. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 2 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-downn and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which has a Flip Effect that lets you choose between Drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, or looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card from it back into the Deck. 1 Lacrima the Crimson Tears. On Normal or Special Summon, it can send a Fiendsmith card from your Deck to the Gy and during your opponent’s turn, you can target a Fiendsmith Link Monster in GY and shuffle it from GY into the Deck to Special Summon that Link Monster. This is really good with Agnumday, and it is something you can do if you start with Scorpio and Monstrosity. 3 Fiendsmith Engraver. You can discard it to add a Fiendsmith Spell/Trap from your Deck to your hand. While it is on field, you can target a Fiendsmith equip card and a monster on the fiend and send both to the GY, and if it is in the GY, you can shuffle 1 other LIGHT Fiend monster from your GY into the Deck/Extra Deck to Special Summon it. 3 Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and 1 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra. On Normal or Special Summon, Scorpio can send a monster from hand to GY to Special Summon a Predaplant monster from Deck other than itself. And if Cobra is Special Summoned by the effect of a Predaplant monster, you can search for a Polymerization Spell Card or a Fusion Spell Card from Deck. 2 Lonefire Blossom which Tributes a Plant to Special Summon a Plant from Deck. 1 Fabled Lurrie which if discarded to GY, it mandatory Special Summons itself. And finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. 

Spell/Traps: 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 3 Fiendsmith’s Tract which searches a LIGHT Fiend and then makes you discard a card. And you can also banish it from GY to Fusion Summon a Fiendsmith Fusion using monsters from your field. 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham or Predaplant Ambulomelides. 1 Pot of Prosperity, 1 Foolish Burial, 1 Called by the Grave. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck is still very tight. 1 Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment and 1 Fiendsmith’s Rex Tremendae. 1 Fiendsmith’s Desirae which requires Fiendsmith Engraver and 2 LIGHT Fiend monsters as Fusion Material. As a Quick Effect, you can negate the effects of face-up cards on the field up to the total Link Rating of the Link Monsters equipped to it until the end of the turn and if it is sent to the GY, you can shuffle 1 other LIGHT Fiend in your GY into the Deck or Extra Deck to target and send a card on field to the GY. 1 Necroquip Princess which is a Level 6 Fusion Monster which needs a monster equipped with a Monster Card and a Fiend Monster Card as Fusion Material and you must Special Summoned her from Extra Deck by sending those cards from your hand and/or field to GY. 1 Master of Ham which is an Instant Fusion target that Special Summons a Flip Monster from hand or Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 Predaplant Ambulomelides which adds a Predaplant monster or a Predap Spell/Trap from Deck, GY, or face-up Extra Deck to hand on Fusion Summon and can Tribute a monster to Special Summon a Predaplant monster from Deck. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or a Ritual Spell if sent to GY. 1 Mereologic Aggregator which is a Rank 9 that sends a monster from your Extra Deck to the GY on Xyz Summon and can target monsters in your GY up to the number of materials it has to detach the same number of materials to attach those monsters in GY to it as material. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Melomelody the Brass Djinn which is a Rank 3 LIGHT Fiend we can make with Scorpio and Cobra to go into Fiendsmith’s Requiem. 1 Fiendsmith’s Agnumday which is a Link-3 that needs 2+ monsters including a LIGHT Fiend. As a soft once per turn, it can Quick Effect target and Special Summon a LIGHT non-Link Fiend from your GY and equip this card to it as an Equip Spell. ANd if it is equipped by this effect, that monster gains ATK equal to the total Link Rating of the Link Monsters equipped to it x600 and it gains piercing damage. 1 Fiendsmith’s Sequence which requires 2 monsters including a LIGHT Fiend as Link Material and can Fusion Summon a Fiend Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck by shuffling materials from your GY into the Deck. And you can target a LIGHT non-Link Fiend monster you control to equip it from field or GY to it as an Equip Spell that prevents your opponent from targeting that monster with card effects. 1 Fiendsmith’s Requiem which is a Link-1 requiring a LIGHT Fiend as material and it can Tribute itself as a Quick Effect to Special Summon a Fiendsmith monster from your hand or Deck and you can equip it from field or GY to a LIGHT non-Link Fiend you control that gives it 600 ATK. And finally, 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 1 Triple Tactics Thrust, 2 Triple Tactics Talent, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, 2 Lightning Storm, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_description:
Hello there! In this deck, we will kill the opponent thanks to Kickfire alongside Maple. Let's get into action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Synchro Summon Maple with whatever you have and choose the Attribute as FIRE. Then, if you go first and your opponent has no monsters, have at least four monsters on your side with Special Summon abilities of Synchro World and Level 1 dudes.

2) Set all four Traps and end your turn. Also, change the button at bottom right corner of the screen to "ON", if you haven't, to not miss anything.

3) When it's your opponent's Draw Phase, activate Needle Ceiling. Its condition was met in #1, so it shouldn't be a problem. Then, chain into 3 x Kickfire. Thanks to Maple, monsters which didn't have FIRE attribute by default contributes to Kickfire.

4) At least four counters were placed onto each individual Kickfire. Next, during Standby Phase, activate 3 x Kickfire to send them to GY and deal 3 x (4 x 1000) = 12000 damage in total to decimate your opponent.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Reinforcement of the Army" can be found by completing the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Into The Void" can be found either within "The Infinite Void" or "Life Force Control System" Secret Packs to save 90 SR!

- "Flower Cardian Moonflowerviewing" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Maple Maiden" can be found within "Artistic Angel" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Junk Converter" + "Junk Speeder" can be found within "Scrap Iron Soldiers" Secret Pack to save 90 SR and 30 UR!

- "Jet Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found either within "Evoked Dragon of Miracles" or "Stardust Ties" Secret Packs to save 60 SR!

- "Junk Synchron" + "Ravenous" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 120 SR.

- These following cards can be found within "Evoked Dragon of Miracles" Secret Pack to save 180 SR and 60 UR:

  • 1 x Stardust Wurm >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x Stardust Synchron >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x Wheel Synchron >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x Stardust Illumination >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x Duelist Genesis >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x On Your Mark, Get Set, DUEL! >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon >>> 30 UR
  • 1 x Crimson Dragon >>> 30 UR

 

So, in total, you can save up to 630 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_description:
Welcome! In this deck, you will take a guess which you knew the answer and win the game.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Use Angel O1 when you have Ra in your hand to Special Summon it. Then, with two more monsters, Normal Summon Ra and lower your LP to 100 with Ra.

2) Play Feather to place a Main Deck card on top of your Main Deck. Then, if you have Scattershot in your hand, play "Reversal Quiz".

3) Since you knew what you have on top of your deck, you knew the answer. With correct one, you can deal final blow with Scattershot.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Junk Synchron" + "Ravenous" + "Reversal Quiz" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 150 SR.

- These following cards can be found within "Evoked Dragon of Miracles" Secret Pack to save 180 SR and 60 UR:

  • 1 x Stardust Wurm >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x Stardust Synchron >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x Wheel Synchron >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x Stardust Illumination >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x Duelist Genesis >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x On Your Mark, Get Set, DUEL! >>> 30 SR

Using the first card pack to make a fiend deck
Dinos that are pure but somehow I won a 100 person tourney at local gamestore with (albeit with slight modifications)!!!

So this deck is fairly nonliner, but inspired by several other decks on this site. I added a few extra copies of lightsworns in the side in case the horus cards aren't doing justice for you. The biggest issue with this deck is shifter decks, with the second biggest issue perhaps stun decks or backrow reliant decks like lab.

This deck is essentially all gas and you can set up synchro minerva and then use the 2 lightsworns you dump, since you'll most likely be making her from lightsworns, 2 more, felis included, to make visas amritara, and voila!

You get access to both of your engines in here. This deck can brick and feel completely dead, but generally, isn't going to lose due to an ash or droll. 

If you REALLY feel that you aren't milling enough, you can swamp Xyz's Minvera for Bujintei or The zombie vamp. I like to set up photon lord first with the horus cards, to then start setting up for lightsworn and tearlaments while protecting from rando hand traps like nib.

deck_description: This could be a potential meta deck that can summon Z-arc and use Yubel and Chimera as a cheap way to search for a fusion card. This deck effectively combines the Yubel and Unchained archetypes to create a versatile strategy that excels in board control and powerful plays. The key mechanic involves using Chimera, the Illusion Beast, to fuse monsters that come from the trap called Soul of the Supreme King into strong fusion monsters like Odd-Eyes Arcray Dragon. You can utilize the Soul of the Supreme King to special summon Z-ARC by banishing it and other necessary monsters from the field, allowing you to leverage the power of those monsters. The synergy between Yubel and Unchained ensures that while you control the board with Yubel’s destructive capabilities, the Unchained cards trigger additional effects when destroyed, allowing you to maintain pressure and extend your plays. ​Overall, the deck provides a strong mix of offense and defense, making it highly adaptable in duels.​

deck_excerpt: Evil HERO deck built for my friend
deck_description: Evil HERO deck built for my friend.

I feel like once a year, I get this HUGE burst of inspiration that lets me cook up something that's just incredible and somehow can play against meta decks, and better yet, something NO-ONE expects to see. First was Phantasm Spiral (a really scuffed list lmao) then P.U.N.K. Fur Hire in 2022 (my third best work), Mannadium Tearlaments in 2023 (my SECOND best work) and now this. Ashened. Volcanic. Snake-Eye. All in one deck.

This, right here, is my BEST work yet. This can take on even the top decks if you master it, and is STILL a fun deck to play, with A LOT of different combo lines. I'm going to give you an overview of each card in the deck, some combos I've come up with, tips to play it, and what the deck really struggles against. Strap in, because this is a VERY LENGTHY guide. At over 4500 words, this is by far the most detailed guide I've ever made for a deck. Lets get into it, and start making 'Pompeii 2 - Electric Boogaloo' a reality, shall we?

==Overview of the Cards==

==Ashened Cards==

Obsidim, The Ashened City

Ashened rely quite heavily on their field spell. Every Ashened monster in your deck can summon themself from your hand if you control Obsidim. You can also use Veidos's effect in hand to give Veidos to your opponent, destroy Obsidim, then summon Priestess with Obsidim's effect if you don't already have Priestess in hand or on field (if you do, any level 4 Ashened monster works). Since it makes all your opponent's monsters Pyro on your turn only, you can fuse their whole field away with Ashened to Endlessness on your turn. In the End Phase, you can also use it's effect to put another copy of itself in your GY on the bottom of the deck, then draw a card.

Extinguishing the Ashened

This card is what usually gets you Veidos, as it sends a level 5 or higher DARK Pyro from your Deck to your GY, however it CAN be hit with Ash Blossom. You can also Fusion Summon by banishing it from your GY, and use monsters from your hand or field as material. However, take note that this card DOES lock you into only Pyro monsters from the Extra Deck after you use the first effect, so try to save it until the end of your combo, after you've hopefully gone full Snake-Eye combo and popped off with Volcanic.

Awakening of Veidos

Now yes, this isn't an Ashened card, but it does support the deck, so I'm including it here. This can also get you Obsidim, and can even get you Veidos or one of the high level Ashened monsters if you're going second and your opponent has a field spell active. This card has the same drawback as Extinguishing, but you are also locked into only summoning Pyros from the Deck, too (not like it really matters, you won't be summoning Diabellstar from the deck anyway). 

Veidos, The Eruption Dragon of Extinction

This card is very important to the deck, as it allows you to destroy your own (or your opponent's) field spell while also setting an Ashened Continuous Trap from your deck. If Veidos goes to the GY from your opponent's field, you can essentially turn it into a board nuke, and destroy all monsters on the field. However this can ONLY happen if it goes to YOUR GY from your OPPONENT'S field. The Quick Effect is really nice, honestly, only downside is that it's during the Main Phase only.

Priestess of the Ashened City

Priestess is the searcher for Ashened. She can Special Summon herself if you have Obsidim on the field (I won't mention this for the rest of the Ashened monsters, because they can all do this), she can add ANY Ashened card  from your Deck except herself, which means she can search Obsidim. She's also a level 4, meaning you can XYZ Summon Banshee using her and another level 4 monster, which there's enough of in this deck. 

Shaman of the Ashened City

OMG TITTIES YESSSSS - oh sorry I was busy admiring those large boobas of Priestess and Shaman.

Anyways, Shaman can shuffle 3 Pyros that are banished or in your GY into your Deck, then you can add an Obsidim if you shuffled an Ashened monster with that effect. Pretty simple, and doesn't come up much, but can be helpful occasionally.

Spearhead of the Ashened City

This guy's just here so he can be a level 4 to make Banshee or to Link Summon one of the many link monsters you have. The bounce effect basically never comes up but it CAN be relevant sometimes. But you should really be using this to make Banshee or to Link Summon instead.

Hero of the Ashened City

Hero can destroy a Pyro monster on the field with it's quick effect in the Main Phase, and if it destroys Veidos with this, you can place an Obsidim from your Deck in your field spell zone. Not bad, but you should try to save this for your opponent's turn so you can nuke the field with Veidos's effect if you need to use it at all.

King of the Ashened City

King allows you to Special Summon any Ashened monster from your hand (this is generally useless because most of the time you'll already have Obsidim on the field). However if you give your opponent Veidos on turn 1, and manage to get out King, you can instead Special Summon any Ashened monster from your deck since your opponent controls a monster with 2800 ATK or more. Do what you will with this information >:)

Ashened to Endlessness

This trap (which you will usually set from Veidos) lets you Fusion Summon on your opponent's turn by using Veidos as a material from your opponent's field (this allows you to use Veidos's effect to nuke, which you should, because the monster you'll usually summon is immune to being destroyed by card effects). On your turn, this is insane, because you can just fuse away most if not ALL of your opponent's field and just go for game with the Veidos fusion monster. The 500 ATK boost for every material you use is a really nice bonus too, because you'll always get at least 1500 extra ATK on the Veidos fusion if you summon it this way. This card can also make all your monsters your opponent currently controls Pyro, until the end of the turn. The only downside to this is that the Fusion Summon effect is Main Phase only, and you can't use materials in hand. Still a GREAT card to fuck your opponent's board up, though.

Ashened for Eternity

This trap lets you get Veidos or an Ashened monster from your GY back to your hand. Most of the time you'll set Endlessness instead of this, but if you can get both set then you'll have solid backrow (this won't always happen though). It also lets you steal your Veidos from your opponent then reduce their monster's ATK by 2800 until the end of the turn. Not a bad card but Endlessness is better.

 

==Volcanic Cards==

Volcanic Emperor

The Volcanic boss monster. Easy summoning condition, just banish 3 Pyros from your field or GY or a Blaze Accelerator card, and BAM. 3100 ATK monster, that will usually burn your opponent for at least 1500, and set a Volcanic Trap from your deck. On top of that, burning your opponent for 500 every time they Special Summon? HOLY SHIT this thing is amazing. This burn stacks too, so... you know where I'm going with this >:)

Volcanic Trooper

The main searcher of the deck, you'll usually add Volcanic Blaze Accelerator or Rocket with the summon effect. The bomb token effect is good, especially if you can discard Rimfire or Shell to use their GY effects. You can even use it to Link Summon Almiraj if you Normal Summoned it. Sadly it isn't level 4 but this next monster is. :)

Volcanic Rocket

A non once per turn search for a Blaze Accelerator card? Yep. Level 4? Yep. Even a decent beater in dire situations? Yep. This card is insane. You can use it to make Banshee, since it's a level 4. You can use it to search Volcanic Blaze Accelerator. There's so many things this card is good for in this deck.

Volcanic Rimfire and Volcanic Shell

There two are under the same heading because they're similar (they both have GY effects). When Rimfire is sent to the GY by any means, you can banish it to send any Volcanic monster from your Deck to the GY (usually Emperor). You can also use Rimfire to banish a Blaze Accelerator card from your GY or face-up field to place a Blaze Accelerator continuous spell/trap on your field. Neither of these effects banish for cost, so they can be hit with Ghost Belle or Called By.

Volcanic Shell, at the cost of 500 LP, can search you another copy of itself while in your GY. That's all it does. But this is VERY useful, as it can let you extend further into your combos. Oh, and did I mention this effect is SOFT once per turn? Yeah... you can extend pretty far with three of these in your deck if you play right.

Blaze Accelerator

This card will NEVER come up, it's only real use is to be sent to the GY to activate its Volcanic counterpart. If you're REALLY desperate you can use it, but I would just use it for its better Volcanic counterpart.

Volcanic Blaze Accelerator

This card is just stupidly good. You have to send your one-of Blaze Accelerator to the GY, but an extra Special Summon of a Volcanic from your hand, AND a way to destroy the bomb tokens you'll probably be giving your opponent? Jesus this this is insane. You can Special Summon a Volcanic from hand so you can save your Normal Summon for your Snake-Eye combo or Ashened combo, too. :)

Volcanic Blaze Accelerator

You could play this with three Scattershots, but I don't have room (literally) for the Scattershots. The GY effect can be helpful to send a Rimfire, Shell, or Emperor from your Deck to the GY, but aside from that, the mulligan on field effect isn't bad either, but I've never had to use it for that.

Volcanic Emission and Volcanic Inferno

Most of the time you'll probably be setting one of these two cards off of Emperor's effect. Emission lets you either Special Summon a Volcanic monster from your Deck and return it to your hand in the End Phase, or burn your opponent for the ATK of one Pyro monster on the field (if you do this it will usually be Veidos). If you burn using a Pyro monster you control, the damage inflicted is halved, so try to use it if your opponent has Veidos. Both effects of this card are good, and it's what you'll usually set first off of Emperor.

Inferno is a negate and burn for 500 if your opponent activates a monster effect on the field, at the cost of banishing a Pyro from your GY. If the banished monster was a Volcanic monster, then you can also negate the effect (it burns for 500 by default). The recycle effect in your opponent's end phase is also nice too, as you can keep going in those longer, grindier games.

 

==Snake-Eye Cards==

Snake-Eye Ash (or SnAsh)

The main starter for your Snake-Eye combo. Be careful since this card is limited to 1, if your opponent hits it with a handtrap and can't stop it, then you might be locked out of your Snake-Eye engine. But this card is insane, that's why they limited it to 1, alongside Poplar. The summon effect lets you add a Snake-Eye monster from your deck to your hand, which will usually be Poplar. You can also use it's other effect to send itself and another face-up card you control (usually Poplar or another Pyro monster) to the GY from the field in order to Special Summon Flamberge from your deck.

Snake-Eye Poplar

If Poplar is added to your hand by any means EXCEPT drawing it, you can Special Summon it. On summon, you can add a Snake-Eye Spell/Trap from your deck to your hand. This will usually be the Snake-Eye field spell, but in some cases you might want to get Original Sinful Spoils instead. Even better, if Poplar goes to the GY from any means, you can place a FIRE monster from your GY in your Spell/Trap (I'll refer to them as S/T from now on) zone as a Continuous Spell. This card is just as good, if not BETTER than SnAsh is, hence why it's also limited.

Snake-Eye Oak

Oak can summon a Level 1 FIRE monster from your GY or banished zone to your field or add it to your hand when it's Normal or Special Summoned. It also shares the same effect as SnAsh, allowing you to summon a Snake-Eye monster from your Deck by sending 2 face-up cards you control to the GY including itself. Overall a great card.

Snake-Eye Diabellstar

Mommy? sorry, Mommy? sorry, Mommy? sorry - oh I got distracted again, sorry.

If she's treated as a Continuous Spell, you can place a FIRE monster from your GY as another Continuos Spell, then Special Summon her from your backrow (yes, for those of you who don't know, this is Snake-Eye's archetypal gimmick - being Continuous Spells. Hmm, reminds me of another deck with Crystals...). The effect on field doesn't come up much, but it can sometimes, when it does it's useful. :)

Snake-Eyes Flamberge Dragon

This card is so stupid, I genuinely think it's banworthy. Until, or IF that happens, we cooking with it. Flamberge is what you'll usually summon off of SnAsh or Oak's second effects. It allows you to place ANY monster in the GY face up in the owner's S/T zone as a Continuous Spell, but also lets you Special Summon a monster treated as a Continuous Spell, but ONLY on your opponent's turn. Now here's the effect why I think Flamberge is ban-worthy (but screw my opinions, they aren't important lol). When Flamberge is sent from the hand or field to the GY, you can Special Summon ANY 2 Level 1 FIRE monsters from your GY. They don't even have to be Snake-Eye monsters, which means you can summon the VOLCANIC Level 1's with this.

Divine Temple of the Snake-Eye

This card will let you, on activation, place a Snake-Eye monster from your deck in your S/T zone as a Continuous Spell. It also boosts your Level 1 FIRE monster's ATK by 1100. AND it lets you Special Summon ANY monster treated as a Continuous Spell when your opponent Normal or Special Summons a monster. This card is goated, no wonder it's banned in the OCG.

Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eye (OSS)

This card, right here, is what lets SO many decks with Level 1 FIRE monsters be playable right now. This deck is no exception, with TWO targets (Rimfire and Shell) in addition to your Snake-Eye Level 1's. By sending another face-up card you control to the GY, you get partial access to your Volcanic engine. What the hell. Oh, and it can also add a Level 1 FIRE monster by banishing itself from your GY, then targeting a Snake-Eye or Diabellstar monster in your GY to place on the bottom of the deck. However, you can ONLY use ONE effect of this card per turn, and if you're like me, you'll never use the GY effect, and in some games that might come back to bite you.

Diabellstar the Black Witch

PLAP PLAP PLAP PLAP PLAP IM BOUTTA BLOW DEEP INSIDE YOU MOMMY OH MY GO-

OH SHIT, sorry guys, you saw nothing, move along please ;)

Yes I'm down so fucking bad for her, how could I not be? With that huge rack of hers, those wide, child-bearing hips and - SHIT I'M GETTING DISTRACTED AGAIN - uhm...

Diabellstar is a staple in 99% of Decks that can run OSS and have an OSS target. Most of the time you'll be searching her with 'Wanted: Seeker of Sinful Spoils' in the Draw Phase to avoid Droll. Rimfire, Emperor, and Shell are utterly AMAZING cards to send to the GY to summon her, and with her effect on summon you'll usually set OSS from the Deck. But yeah, she's an amazing card to have in basically every deck these days. 

I bet she'd be amazing in bed too... DAMN IT STOP BEING SO HORNY

Wanted: Seeker of Sinful Spoils

You'll be adding Diabellstar with this, but if you open her instead of this then its fine. However if you are out of plays you can banish this from your GY after you've also used OSS on field, sent OSS to the GY (without using it's effect on field), or after you've used the GY effect of OSS. This will place the OSS on the bottom of the deck and draw 1.

 

=Other Staples==

Bonfire

This searches any starter for any of the three archetypes you're playing in this deck. This card is insane. Enough said. :)

One for One

This can start your Snake-Eye combo off, and if you can send Rimfire, Emperor, or Shell to the GY for cost, it's even better. You can even summon Rimfire or Shell if you're desperate or want to screw with your opponent a little. :)

 

God this is already 2800 words long and I haven't even gotten to the Extra Deck yet. What the fuck dude.

 

==The Extra Deck==

Embers of the Ashened

You'll usually summon this with the GY effect of Extinguishing, using any 2 Pyro monsters. It allows you to recycle Obsidim or Divine Temple, which is a plus. It's also good if you can make it going second since it can destroy one of your opponent's Pyro monsters if it battles, and on your turn it can attack again if you do this. Not terrible, and can help you win some games, but the recycle effect is great.

Veidos, the Dragon of Endless Darkness

Now THIS is a fucking awesome boss monster. You'll usually make this with the effect of Endlessness, using Veidos from your opponent's field and 2 or more Pyros monsters on the field (possibly using a bomb token you gave your opponent with a Volcanic monster as one material, too). In combination with regular Veidos, this can potentially wipe your opponent's whole board (regular Veidos is all monsters on the field, and this Veidos is your opponent's S/T cards). However, this card CANNOT be destroyed by card effects, meaning Veidos's nuke effect does nothing to it. If you use Endlessness to summon this, it'll have at minimum 4500 ATK. I've actually been able to get this to 7000 ATK and just straight up won the game because of it the ATK boost. Oh, on top of that, it also has an effect where when your opponent activates a card or effect on the field, you can destroy that card. I LOVE this thing as a boss monster.

Infernal Flame Banshee

If you are able to make Banshee, she'll allow you to access to the last (or one of) the engines in your deck you haven't started using yet. She can add ANY Pyro monster or send ANY Pyro monster from your Deck to the GY. You need Emperor in your GY? Banshee can make that happen. You need Poplar to start Snake-Eye'ing all over your opponent? She's got that covered, too. You need an Ashened monster to extend your plays? Yep. God she's such a good card.

She's made out of fire, so I wonder what it'd be like if I couldn't get burned so I we could fu - NO, NO MORE HORNY. STOP.

Back to the important stuff - you can actually banish her to summon Emperor, and then summon her back to use as material for more combos. Insane synergy.

Amphibious Swarmship Amblowhale (Whale), Salamangreat Raging Phoenix (Raging), and Worldsea Dragon Zealantis (Zealantis)

These are the extra deck monsters you want to try end your turn with on the board. If you can end your turn with Whale and Zealantis on the board, with a Raging in the GY, you're set and you'll be pretty resilient to having your board broken, too.

Whale is mainly a big beater to have, but the effect on destruction can get back any Link-3 or lower monster from the GY (usually Promethean). Plus the OTHER GY effect is nice too, to destroy a card on the field if a Link-3 or lower monster is destroyed by battle or card effect while Whale's in your GY.

You'll usually use Raging to make Zealantis, but you also use Whale to do so as well if you need to. Raging's GY effect is insane, letting you summon it from the GY if a FIRE monster you control is destroyed by battle or card effect, then you can give Raging extra ATK equal to what was destroyed (which is permanent).

Zealantis can let you break your opponent's board and/or trigger some of your monster effects on your opponent's turn, by re-Special Summoning them from the banished zone after you use Zealantis to nuke the board.

Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy and Hiita the Fire Charmer, Ablaze

You can use ANY Ashened monster or Diabellstar to make Dharc and ANY Snake-Eye or Volcanic monster to make Hiita, and steal a monster with the corresponding attribute from your opponent's GY to keep cooking (e.g. Hiita can steal Ash Blossom from your opponent's GY and you can use that to keep comboing). Plus their effects on destruction are nice too. Dharc can actually search Veidos with his GY effect, so that's a REALLY nice touch, too. 

Oh I also want Hiita to squish me between her thighs~

I:P Masquerena and S:P Little Knight

I want these two in a three-way so fucking badly- *Sigh*. You know what, I'm not even going to try and stop myself anymore. 

I:P can go into Promethean or any Link-2 or higher Link monster, and give it protection from being destroyed by card effects. Plus she has really big and soft titties~. She can even make S:P if you really need to.

S:P is stupidly OP. You can make her with Anima, Almiraj or any other Extra Deck monster and you got yourself a free banish. You can even use that effect to banish your OWN Pyro monsters, to let Emperor's burn effect hit just that little bit harder. Plus the banish 2 monsters effect is also insane.

Her boobs look just as soft as I:P's do~

Promethean Princess

Ah, one of my beloved FIRE waifus~

She can summon ANY FIRE monster back from your GY (usually you'll get Flamberge back if you play the deck right and you don't get handtrapped / you play through handtraps) Oh, she also needs ANY two or more effect monsters to summon, so that's a bonus. She does lock you into FIRE monsters while she's on the field, but you can just make Raging or Blowhale with her and then you're not locked any more. Her GY effect to reborn herself and destroy a FIRE monster you control and a moster your opponent controls when your opponent Special Summons is great, too.

Relinquished Anima and Salamangreat Almiraj

These two serve the a very similar purpose - to extend your plays or enable more. Almiraj can be used to get Rimfire in the GY if you have to resort to Normal Summoning Rimfire, or it can also be summoned with any of the Level 1 Snake-Eye monsters, Volcanic Trooper or Volcanic Shell (but they have to have been Normal Summoned in order to do this, since Almiraj requires 1 Normal Summoned Monster with 1000 or less ATK).

Anima can be made by using any of the Level 1 Snake-Eye monsters, Rimfire, or Shell. You can use it if you're going second to punish your opponent for summoning a boss monster in a zone Anima will point to, by stealing their monster and equipping it to Anima. Plus you can then use Anima and another monster to make S:P, and get S:P's on summon effect to banish a card on the field or the GY.

 

==Weaknesses==

First thing's first, this deck CAN brick at times, which sucks. When it doesn't, you'll probably be fine depending on whether your opponent has interruptions or not.

You'll notice in the side deck I'm playing cards which stop banishing (e.g. Lancea, Crossout, and Called By for Shifter). This deck loses HARD to Shifter, Dimensional Fissure, or Macro Cosmos (anything that stops your cards [particularly your monsters] from going to the GY). If your opponent hits you with one or more of these and you don't have an out, you're basically fucked. Lancea DOES stop some of your combos, but for the price of stopping Shifter and COMPLETELY shutting down Ritual Beast, it's 100% worth it. 

That said, this deck also stuggles against certain floodgates. Rivalry of Warlords isn't a huge problem for you, but There Can Be Only One (TCBOO) fucks you over so unbelievably hard its unreal. You are able to play under Gozen Match and Anti-Spell Fragrance, but you won't be able to do anywhere near as much as you normally can if either (or both) are on the field.

To counter this, you could replace the one-of handtraps (except Shifter) in the side deck with backrow removal to deal with these floodgates (if your opponent plays these cards, that is).

Droll can also hinder you quite a bit, but you can still end on a moderate endboard even if you do get hit by it.

The Mulcharmy monsters ... yeah I'll be real with you, you basically insta-lose to Purulia and will struggle to play through Fuwalos, but it IS possible to do without giving your opponent much card advantage.

One thing to note is that Veidos actually turns off your opponent's Imperms and the Mulcharmy monsters if you go first and give it to them early (but you might lock youself into Pyros with Extinguishing or Awakening unless you open Veidos and the field spell)

 

==Combos==

Now since this guide is already over 4200 words long, I'll try to keep this section brief.

I'm not going to give you any specific combos, but I will say, try to save the Ashened engine for last, since Extinguishing and Awakening both lock you into Pyro monsters from the Extra Deck and both Decks, respectively. If I give you even 1 full combo line, this would be at at least 5000 words long, and I doubt most of you will have time to read it.

If you're forced to use your Ashened engine first, you can still possibly make Banshee and access the Volcanic or Snake-Eye engine (if you haven't used Awakening of Veidos, go for Snake-Eye if you're confident you can play it without using the Extra Deck. Otherwise, just go for the Volcanic engine).

In a perfect world, the engine order should be like this:

Snake-Eye -> Volcanic -> Ashened

However this isn't a perfect world so you may only get access to two engines or even one if you're REALLY unlucky. In that case, I'd go:

Snake-Eye -> Volcanic

Volcanic -> Ashened (can be other way around as well, since you may not use the Extra Deck much, if at all)

Snake-Eye -> Ashened

 

==Conclusion==

Jesus fucking christ, this is over 4500 words at this point. Guess it goes to show how much I like this deck and how fun and versatile it is, right?

If you actually read everything above, holy shit, you are one dedicated motherfucker. You have my praise :)

I will update this guide with a Youtube Link to a combo video eventually (probably in the coming weeks)

Hope this guide helps you start causing natural disasters and beginning Pompeii 2 - Electric Boogaloo

Oh, and one last thing~

 

 

 

 

And the walls, kept tumbling down in the city that we looooooooooove

Great clouds roll over the hills, bringing darkness from abooooooooove

*drum fill*

BUT IF YOU CLOSE YOUR EYES

DOES IT ALMOST FEEL LIKE NOTHING CHANGED AT ALL?

AND IF YOU CLOSE YOUR EYES

DOES IT ALMOST FEEL LIKE YOU'VE BEEN HERE BEFORE?

 

Thank You, everyone, and goodnight.

CrankyBoy

deck_description:

Placement: Top 8
There's only 3 fairy monsters, and they are all weak, this is the pain of using only cards from the first card set.

Jaden Yuki is the main protagonist in the GX series and this is an elemental hero deck profile.

There are so many "Hero" cards in this archetype with many sub-archetypes like "masked", "destiny", "evil", "vision", "xtra", "elemental", "neos - spacians". This deck is mostly (around 95%) "Elemental Hero" cards.

The main focus of this build is to have easy access to polymerization. Not only that, but most of the cards are kind of searchable with the help of "Giant Rat", "E - Emergency call" and "Elemental Hero Stratos". 

The big problem of the deck is that you have to lose your normal summon most of the times, that's why it's important to be aware of the resources you are spending. "Elemental hero Woodsman" can be special summoned in your opponent's turn through "Giant Rat", so in your turn you can recycle "Polymerization" from grave.

The biggest advantage of this deck is that most cards can be used as fusion materials cause there are no "BIG" restrictions. The playmaker of this deck is "Elemental hero Sunrise" whose can help you fusion summon again in the same turn another monster too.

One cool mechanic to abuse vs players that are mostly using mirror forces cards is to, summon "Elemental Hero solid soldier" then special summon from hand "Elemental Hero Stratos" and destroy some spell/trap cards on the field.

Some of my cards are quite slow for the modern standards  to give consistency to the deck, some of them are "Giant Rat" and "Elemental Hero Woodsman". To help with this slow paced gameplay, I use "one day of peace", "swords of revealing light" and "storming mirror force".

The main difference of this deck, compared to others, is that I use easier to execute combos by not combining all the available other hero sub-archetypes. Instead I am trying to take advantage of cards like "Skyscraper" and "Elemental Hero Honest Neos" to boost up the attack of my weak monsters. While most of my monsters are level 4, I could add more XYZ cards (Number 27: Dreadnought Dreadnoid or even Utopia engine), but I don't like this approach.

Some cards might not have the best ratios or can be replaced by similar cards. Some of them could be: the second "Skyscraper", the x2 "Storming Mirror Force" and x2 "Lightning Storm" but this is debatable.

deck_excerpt: Type Zero Magic Crusher FTK ft. Fortune Lady Water
deck_description:
Greetings! This is an introduction to "Fortune Lady Water" decks as a whole. It's like "Junk Speeder" decks, where you will be locked into Synchro Summons. Can be easier to guide if compared to Junk decks because Fortune decks will heavily revolve around resummoning Cardian and Water with "De-Synchro" to draw lots of cards. However, don't expect to draw like how you would in Junk decks. It's tricky in that regard. Without further ado, let's bounce!

 

 

Gameplan

1) You have two ways to start with:

  • If you don't have Past in your hand but you have Vision, use Vision to find Past and Normal Summon Past. Then, draw until you find Calling while Light + Water is in your Main Deck. Use Calling to bring forth Light and use Past to banish Light, which lets you raise the level of Past to 2. Getting rid of Light results into Water being summoned from your Main Deck and you can start drawing.
  • If you have Past and Vision in your hand, Normal Summon Past. Then, use Vision to find Calling and rest is same as above.

2) Synchro Summon Tri-Edge with Past and Water. Then, play "De-Synchro" to bring Past and Water back. Since you have Past beforehand, Water lets you draw 2 cards.

3) Use Souls to send "Illusion of Chaos" and Special Summon Souls. After using the ability of Souls to draw cards, Synchro Summon Cardian with Past + Souls + Water. You can draw a card with Cardian and repeat with "De-Synchro" until you have nothing left to draw...

  • Excavation is here to fetch De-Synchro. However, if your UR budget is tight, you can consider using "Spell Reproduction" instead. Feel free to check it in Side Deck.
  • "Dark Dimension Soldier" is here, in case you either couldn't find Souls or had to banish Souls with Allure while you have De-Synchro in your hand. Soldier = Past + Water is your equation and if you have banished Souls, you can revive it with Soldier.
  • Though you can do it only once per turn, you can draw 2 cards with Ravenous, if you use Hat Tricker along the way. Ravenous = Hat + Water + Past is the equation and feel free to add Ravenous and Hat, if you wish. You can check them in Side Deck.

4) Make sure you have either played "Fortune's Future" on Light or send Formula to GY. "Past + Souls = Formula" and "Formula + Water = Stardust or Tri-Edge" are your equations. This step is needed because you should have a LIGHT monster in your GY to Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon.

5) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop. Then, activate Temple >>> Crusher.

6) If you have any Spells but "Primal Seed" in your hand, send them to BZ with Crusher and deal 500 damage to your opponent for each. Then, find them with "Primal Seed" and repeat with Crusher until either your opponent is dead or resigns.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- You don't have to craft "Magical Stone of Excavation" to save 60 UR! If you are low on UR, I must insist you crafting "Spell Reproduction" instead. Feel free to check in Side Deck.

- "Magicians' Souls" + "Illusion of Chaos" can be collected by purchasing "Vortex of Magic" deck. 120 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Flower Cardian Moonflowerviewing" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Sacred Sword of Seven Stars" can be found within "Celestial Dragon and Bear" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Duelist Genesis" + "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Evoked Dragon of Miracles" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Allure of Darkness" + "Into The Void" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Primal Seed" + "Dark Dimension Soldier" + "Type Zero Magic Crusher" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

- "Temple of the Kings" can be found either within "The Ones Who Serve Ra" or "Guardian of Kings" Secret Packs to save 30 SR!

- These cards can be found within "Destiny's Sorceress" Secret Pack to save 150 SR and 90 UR:

  • 1 x Fortune Lady Light >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x Fortune Lady Water >>> 30 SR
  • 3 x Fortune Vision >>> 90 SR
  • 3 x Fortune Lady Calling >>> 90 UR

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 330 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_description: live twins have a neat synergy with fiendsmith lol

The Deck Has So Many Ways of Going First.

 

One Desired End Board Involves Lancea, Gymir and If Possible Some Ice Baarier Lockdowns Like Wayne with Giorgius (Preventing Graveyard Effects and Banishing Spells/Traps). Punish Your Opponent's Special Summons With Lancea Summons For Raiho and Medium.

Starry Knight Control Deck With a Small Voiceless Voice Engine

This deck is centered around the LIGHT Fairy-type Starry Knight archetype, featuring the powerful Level 7 LIGHT Dragon, Starry Night. When summoned, Starry Night can destroy a card on the field. Additionally, when Starry Night returns to your hand, other Starry Knight cards activate their effects, allowing you to draw cards and generate significant advantage.

To complement the Starry Knight strategy, this deck includes a small Voiceless Voice engine. Sauravis (VV), another Level 7 LIGHT Dragon, can return to your hand to summon Sauravis (AA). When Sauravis (AA) returns to your hand, it can negate a summon.

The main strategy is to control the game by utilizing the removal effects of Starry Knight and the disruption provided by Sauravis. By efficiently managing your hand and field, this deck excels in creating advantageous situations and overwhelming your opponent over time.

Overall, this Starry Knight Control deck, enhanced by the Voiceless Voice engine, is ideal for players who enjoy a strategic, control-oriented playstyle.

deck_excerpt: Purify your opponents monsters, board and lifepoints with the blazing flames of Armageddon with Infernoid Snake-Eye!
deck_description:
Infernoids have always been a powerful deck, but it has been historically plagued as being bricky and slow as hell (pun intended), its need to main 12-18 bricks, un-normal summonable maindeck monsters, and the lack of tools to bring sufficient numbers of its monsters to the graveyard. 
 
Until now! The support for Infernoids from the selection pack "Outlaws from the Inferno" is what kids today might call "cracked!" Infernoid Evil's foolish burial of up to ELEVEN Infernoid bodies to the GY is unmatched by any other card in Yugioh. Not only that, it searches for any Infernoid spell/trap from deck when it reaches the GY or banished, further enabling your consistency! The new archtypal boss monster, Infernoid Flood is also nothing to scoff at, since it negates a summon, banishes from field, and floats into any Infernoid from deck when destroyed. Oh, and the rest of the Infernoid spell/trap support is also incredible - they're all very decent! 
 
When paired with Snake-Eye, Infernoid has definitely modernized enough to be a new powerhouse in the Masterduel meta, despite the hits to Snake-Eye in the recent banlists. Grass Looks Greener is also legal in Masterduel, and this card (if it resolves) turns Infernoid into an unstoppable juggernaut - you basically win when it resolves! Like in the Duel Terminal Lore, Infernoids will be a flood of purifying inferno to every unfortunate deck it comes across!

With "That Grass Looks Greener" legal in Masterduel, Infernoid has an insane "instant-win-button" with such a powerful card that is searchable with x3 Thrust and x3 Left Arm Offering! Even without the grass, Infernoid is still a GY combo juggernaut that can reliably go first or second as a 60 card pile, very much like Branded! With all the new support and banlist unhits, Infernoid is now a force to be reckoned with that can easily combat even powerful tier 1 meta!
 
Purify your opponents monsters, board and lifepoints with the blazing flames of Armageddon with Infernoid Snake-Eye!
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

If you want a detailed guide on how to play this deck, click here!
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: People love watchin a fire burn
deck_description:
People love watchin a fire burn

Standard format yugioh deck

Beginner friendly

A Tutorial Combo

Normal Summon Aluber, activate effect of Aluber to add Branded Fusion from deck to hand.

Activate Branded Fusion, send Fallen of Albaz and The Bystial Lubellion from your deck to the graveyard, fusion summon Albion, the Branded Dragon from your extra deck in defense position.

Activate the effect of Albion on it's summon to banish Aluber from your field and Albaz from your graveyard, fusion summon Lubellion, the Searing Dragon in defense position.

Activate the effect of Lubellion, the Searing Dragon on it's fusion summon to discard any 1 card, then shuffle itself back into the extra deck and shuffle Fallen of Albaz from your banishment back into your main deck, then fusion summon into Mirrorjade, the Iceblade Dragon.

Activate the effect of The Bystial Lubellion in your graveyard to tribute Albion, the Branded Dragon from your field, allowing you to summon The Bystial Lubellion.

Activate the effect of The Bystial Lubellion to place Branded Lost from your deck face up into your spell and trap zone.

deck_name: Pure Superheavy (very casual so no real non-engine)
deck_description:
It's basically a pure Superheavy list for a more casual setting (or for someone who's starting out and wants to learn Synchro and Pendulum) where people want to avoid hand traps. The deck is mosty staying within its archetype bar the Crimson Dragon package in the Extra Deck and the Kaijus in the main (to abuse Battleball) and since Superheavy Samurai need a Graveyard devoid of any Spells or Traps we of course don't run any of those. (Sekka's Light might seem interesting for us but it blocks us from activating Pendulums so I rather don't run it)

Of course many of the cards from this list can be switched for higher power cards and for example a good chunk of the Soul lineup can be changed to non-engine hand traps instead for more competitive viability and 

What you summon with Crimson Dragon is entirely up to your preference but I've added some options to the Side Deck for now (Dis Pater and Sifr Divine Dragon eat up a bit more money than some trying to get into the game might be willing to spend from the start or for a casual setting)

If y'all have some questions about some card choices and their interactions feel free to leave a comment

deck_excerpt: Duel Academy FTK ft. Fortune Lady Water
deck_description:
Hello there! It's yet another "Primal Seed" loop with "Fortune Lady Water". You can check the previous one here.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop.

2) Place "Duel Academy" and Synchro Summon Brionac. Then, play "Primal Seed". Since you have Brionac, which is Sea Serpent, you can deal 1000 damage with "Duel Academy".

3) To reset "Duel Academy", place another copy on the field. Next, fetch other copy from BZ with "Primal Seed" while dealing 1000 damage via "Duel Academy" again. Since this step is a loop, repeat until your opponent is dead.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- You don't have to craft "Magical Stone of Excavation" to save 90 UR! If you are low on UR, I must insist you crafting "Spell Reproduction" instead. Feel free to check in Side Deck.

- "Magicians' Souls" + "Illusion of Chaos" can be collected by purchasing "Vortex of Magic" deck. 90 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Flower Cardian Moonflowerviewing" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Duelist Genesis" + "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Evoked Dragon of Miracles" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Allure of Darkness" + "Into The Void" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Primal Seed" + "Dark Dimension Soldier" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 30 SR and 60 UR!

- These cards can be found within "Destiny's Sorceress" Secret Pack to save 150 SR and 90 UR:

  • 1 x Fortune Lady Light >>> 30 SR
  • 1 x Fortune Lady Water >>> 30 SR
  • 3 x Fortune Vision >>> 90 SR
  • 3 x Fortune Lady Calling >>> 90 UR

 

So, in total, you can save up to 450 SR and 330 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

Add and subtract as you desire. Staple cards are absent because you probably know about them already. So I filled the side deck with cards you should consider, that you might not know about. Remember to have fun! And I don't do commissions.

anime inspired deck for weevil underwood from his duel against yugi

Dragster vs Speeder, who is the fastest? Who will be the winner? We can rev the engine to find out, right?

 

 

Gameplan

1) Make sure you have played at least 1 x Upstart Goblin and use "De-Synchro" in following cases only:

  • Jet Synchron + Wheel Synchron = Stardust Charge Warrior >>> De-Synchro >>> Jet Synchron + Wheel Synchron = Coral Dragon
  • Ravenous + Junk Synchron = Crimson Dragon >>> De-Synchro >>> Ravenous + Junk Synchron = Centur-Ion Legatia
  • Cardian + Level 1 = AFD/APD >>> De-Synchro >>> Cardian + Level 1 = Dragster

2) When Dragster is present onboard, place all "F.A." cards to raise the level of Dragster until you reach 12. You can also raise with Pendulum ability of Risebell as well. Speaking of Pendulums, place Risebell and Moissa on Pendulum Zones.

3) Place "Light Barrier" and Pendulum Summon The World and rest of other monsters to fill your board. Choose the outcome for The World as heads to skip your opponent's turn at the cost of sending two of your monsters to GY, which will be Cockroach + Balerdroch.

4) Place "Black Garden" and end your turn. Skip your opponent's turn with The World and send Cockroach + Balerdroch to GY, be it with The World or due to big handspace.

5) If you couldn't have raised the level of Dragster to 12, use Risebell each turn on Dragster while bringing forth Cockroach + Balerdroch constantly and sending these two with The World to skip a turn. Meanwhile, "Black Garden" plants the roses to opposing side.

6) Attack into flowers with Dragster each turn, triggering "F.A. Winners" three times in total to banish all three "F.A." Field Spells. Thus, you win the duel with "F.A. Winners".

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Reinforcement of the Army" can be found by completing the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Into The Void" can be found either within "The Infinite Void" or "Life Force Control System" Secret Packs to save 90 SR!

- "Flower Cardian Moonflowerviewing" + "Arcana Force XXI - The World" + "Light Barrier" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 60 SR and 30 UR!

- "Doomking Balerdroch" can be found within "Abyssal Underworld" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "F.A. Dawn Dragster" can be found within "Tournament Athletes" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Junk Converter" + "Junk Speeder" can be found within "Scrap Iron Soldiers" Secret Pack to save 90 SR and 30 UR!

- "Black Garden" can be found within "Exquisite Jet-Black Rose" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Jet Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Junk Synchron" + "Ravenous" + "Ancient Pixie Dragon" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 120 SR and 30 UR!

- These following cards can be found within "Evoked Dragon of Miracles" Secret Pack to save 180 SR and 90 UR:

deck_excerpt: New water supports post ROTA feat ghotis
deck_description:
The main line is the classic mermail atlantean combo, then with abysshrine you go for Coelacanth, summon shif OR keaf and some level 4 (better if you have one Dragoons on the field) and use them to summon behemoth and arionpos, banish psiics from deck, psiics banish shif and search snopios then banish itself. At this point you detach Dragoons to summon the toad, Dragoons triggers and search for some starter and continue the combo.

The end board you get is with toad, neptabyss (maybe with abyssalacia), arionpos, snopios and heavy infantry in hand. In standby you can special summon shif from banished and go for full ghoti combo.

The ghoti combo is difficult to use, because Deep Beyond banishes everything, but it can be so useful at the end of the main phase, or in a difficult situation. So be sure to have some starter in the hand, abyssalacia and abysshrine are perfect to search that.

That combo can be strong, but fragile. If you want to have more consinstency you can go for the normal mermail combo. I don't know how to make the side deck yet, but you can make one to replace ghoti engine if necessary with some handtraps and staples like Zealantis, Trishula or Stealth Kragen, maybe you can use crossout and TTT or D barrier.

If you wanna give me some advice or have some question you can dm me on ig @Goffry__. Have fun!

deck_name: Jaden Yuki - Elemental Hero Neos / Rainbow Dragon (LOTD:LE)
deck_description:
This deck is quite tricky to use, that's why I need to guide you.Elemental Hero Neos / Neo-Spacian cards have a quite outdated mechanic for the modern standards.

To make them playable enough, you need to skip most Neo-Spacian cards and their Fusion counterparts. I would like to cut-down 1 Neos but "Miracle Fusion" (banish materials) is on the way and without Neos you can't play the game at all."Keeper of the dragon magic" basically enables the whole deck. By discarding 1 card you can search for "Neos Fusion". "Neos Fusion" can summon "Rainbow Neos" which is among the strongest cards of the game cause, it can destroy pretty much everything on the field.

While most old Neos fusion monsters return to the deck at the END PHASE, these new Neos Fusion monsters do not. In your next turn you can always use "Miracle contact" to summon again 1 "Rainbow Neos" and recycle the materials into the deck.

One nice mechanic is that you can use "Neos Fusion" by sending as materials "Elemental hero Neos" and "Elemental HERO Liquid Soldier". This way you can draw 2 cards, while you create a nice setup for the next turn to "Miracle fusion"/"Miracle contact" from grave to draw gain 2 cards.

I feel like there are times that you don't get to hand the best cards possible, that's why this deck has "Card Destruction" and "Morphing jar". You might have to run "Neo space connector" up to x3 copies and Neos to x2.

Via "Neo space connector" and "Keeper of the dragon magic" you cansummon Neos quite easily without problem and with "Wrath of Neos" you can destroy all the cards on the field.

The only Neo-Spacian monsters I am using are, "Neo-Spacian Air Hummingbird" and "Neo-Spacian Glow Moss" cause their Fusion counterparts are decent enough.

Legacy of the Duelist Link Evolution is not a fast-paced game as Master Duel is. And it might be possible to use all Neo-Spacians in the deck for nostalgia reasons. But as you can see from this deck, you don't really need them, while all of these Fusion monsters takes so much space from the extra deck.

"Elemental Hero Brave Neos" fusion monster is one of the best to search for a Neos spell/trap card.While "Elemental Hero Neos Knight" is quite good to kill 2 monsters in a turn (vs "Gravekeeper's Spy" and "Gravekeeper's Nobleman" for example).
